"question": "Give an example of a time you had limited information but still had to make a recommendation.",
"situation": "In an internship project, I was asked to estimate demand for a new digital service in a market where the company had no historical sales data.",
"task": "I had to create a defensible recommendation using imperfect external data and a short timeline.",
"action": "I broke the problem into market size, adoption rate, pricing, and customer acquisition assumptions. I used public reports, competitor pricing, and internal customer survey data to create conservative, base, and aggressive scenarios. I clearly labeled each assumption and pressure-tested the model with two managers from sales and finance. I also included a sensitivity table showing that adoption rate and churn were the two variables that most affected profitability.",
"result": "The recommendation helped leadership approve a limited pilot instead of a full launch. The pilot reached 1,200 users in eight weeks and stayed within 7% of my base-case demand estimate.",
"tags": ["dealing with ambiguity", "market sizing", "business judgment", "consulting"]
