"question": "Tell me about a time you used data to make a decision.",
"situation": "As a junior commercial analyst, I noticed that promotional budgets were being allocated based mostly on last year's spend rather than current outlet performance.",
"task": "I wanted to recommend a better allocation method that improved return on promotional investment.",
"action": "I collected outlet-level sales, promotion spend, foot traffic estimates, and historical growth for the previous six months. I grouped outlets into performance tiers and calculated incremental sales per dollar of promotion. I found that the middle tier was generating the best marginal return, while some top-tier outlets were receiving spend despite limited incremental uplift. I presented a reallocation plan that shifted 15% of spend from low-return outlets to high-potential middle-tier outlets.",
"result": "The revised allocation improved promotional ROI by 11% over the next quarter. It also became the template for monthly budget review discussions with the sales team.",
"tags": ["data-driven decision making", "commercial analytics", "ROI analysis", "strategy"]
},
